declare(strict_types=1);
echo '<div class="mk-prose">';
echo '<p class="mk-muted" style="margin-top:0;">A comparative thesis on metempsychosis, reincarnation, and karma across all major religious and esoteric traditions — with doctrines, variants, and distinctions.</p>';

echo '<h2>Definitions</h2>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Metempsychosis</strong> (Greek: meta + empsychos — "change of soul") — the transmigration of the soul from one body to another after death; the broadest term, encompassing both human-to-human and human-to-animal/plant transmigration.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Reincarnation</strong> — specifically the rebirth of a soul in a new human body; a subset of metempsychosis where the return is specifically to human form.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Palingenesis</strong> — "rebirth" in a general sense; used in some philosophical traditions to describe cosmic cycles of destruction and renewal, not only individual souls.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Karma</strong> (Sanskrit: "action") — the law of moral causation; the doctrine that every action creates consequences that shape future experience, in this life or future lives. Each tradition has its own version of this principle, by different names.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#b7791f;">⊕ Metempsychosis in Ancient and Classical Traditions</h2>';

echo '<h3>Orphism (Greece, c. 600 BCE)</h3>';
echo '<p>The Orphic tradition — Greek mystery religion claiming descent from the mythical poet Orpheus — is one of the earliest Greek doctrines of metempsychosis. Orphic texts (gold tablets found in graves) taught that the soul is divine but imprisoned in the body as punishment for a primordial crime (the Titans\' murder of Dionysus). The soul undergoes repeated incarnations — human, animal, and plant — until it is sufficiently purified. At each death the soul must avoid the spring of Forgetfulness (Lethe) and drink instead from the spring of Memory (Mnemosyne) to retain its identity across lives. After sufficient purification, the soul escapes the cycle of rebirth and joins the divine. <strong>Gender</strong>: souls can incarnate in any gender or species.</p>';

echo '<h3>Pythagoreanism (Greece, c. 500 BCE)</h3>';
echo '<p>Pythagoras of Samos (c. 570–495 BCE) taught metempsychosis and claimed to remember his own previous lives — including a life as Euphorbus, a Trojan warrior. Pythagorean metempsychosis was explicitly cross-species: humans could be reborn as animals and vice versa. This led to the Pythagorean prohibition against eating meat (you might be eating a former human) and against harming animals. The criterion for the quality of rebirth was the life lived: a virtuous life led to a better next incarnation; a vicious life to a worse one, possibly as an animal. <strong>Gender</strong>: not specified as fixed; the soul could incarnate in different sexes.</p>';

echo '<h3>Platonic Philosophy (Greece, c. 400 BCE)</h3>';
echo '<p>Plato is the most important transmitter of metempsychosis doctrine in Western philosophy. In the <em>Phaedo</em>, <em>Republic</em> (the Myth of Er), <em>Phaedrus</em>, and <em>Timaeus</em>, Plato presents metempsychosis as philosophical fact. The soul is immortal, pre-existent, and survives death. In the Myth of Er (Republic X), souls choose their next life before drinking the water of Lethe (forgetfulness) and being born. The choice is free but conditioned by the soul\'s character from previous lives. Cross-species incarnation is possible: a tyrant might become a wolf; a philosopher might become a bee. <strong>Gender</strong>: in the <em>Timaeus</em>, Plato states that a man who lives badly will be reborn as a woman — revealing the patriarchal assumptions of Greek thought. A woman who lives badly becomes an animal. This is a morally weighted hierarchy alien to modern sensibility.</p>';
echo '<p><strong>Karma equivalent</strong>: the soul\'s choices and character in previous lives determine the quality of future incarnations. Justice is cosmically administered across lives.</p>';

echo '<h3>Neoplatonism (3rd–6th century CE)</h3>';
echo '<p>Plotinus accepted metempsychosis following Plato. Souls descend from the World Soul into bodies through a process of increasing individuation. After death, the soul\'s trajectory depends on its level of philosophical attainment. A soul that has lived philosophically returns to a human body or potentially to a higher non-embodied state. A soul that has lived in sensuality may return in an animal body suited to those desires. Plotinus agreed with Plato\'s cross-species transmigration but emphasized that the philosophical life could break the cycle entirely through henosis (union with the One). <strong>Gender</strong>: follows Plato; not explicitly elaborated.</p>';

echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#2d6a1f;">⊕ Reincarnation in Indian Traditions</h2>';

echo '<h3>Hinduism — Punarjanma (Sanskrit: "rebirth")</h3>';
echo '<p>Hindu doctrine of reincarnation (punarjanma or samsara) is the most elaborated in human history. Every living being — human, animal, plant, insect, divine being — is a soul (Atman or Jiva) cycling through births and deaths driven by karma and desire (vasana). The quality and form of the next incarnation is determined by the accumulated karma of previous lives: good actions create merit (punya) and lead to better rebirths; bad actions create demerit (papa) and lead to worse rebirths. The entire cosmic hierarchy — from the lowest worm to the highest deity — is part of the same samsaric system.</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Cross-species transmigration</strong>: fully accepted. A human soul can be reborn as an animal, insect, or plant if karma warrants it. Conversely, an animal soul progresses through higher forms toward human birth. Human birth is considered especially precious because it is the only form in which liberation (moksha) can be actively pursued.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Gender in reincarnation</strong>: Hindu tradition generally allows souls to incarnate in different genders across lives. A man may be reborn as a woman and vice versa. Gender, like species, is a function of karma. However, certain Hindu texts treat the female birth as less spiritually advantageous than the male (reflecting historical patriarchal bias rather than intrinsic doctrine). Tantric Hinduism explicitly affirms the equal spiritual status of male and female incarnations.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Karma</strong>: the most developed karma doctrine in any tradition. Three types: Sanchita (accumulated karma from all past lives), Prarabdha (karma being experienced in the current life), and Kriyamana/Agami (karma being created now for future lives). Liberation (moksha) involves the exhaustion of all karma — particularly Prarabdha — and the cessation of new karma creation through desireless action (karma yoga) or wisdom (jnana yoga).</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Liberation from samsara</strong>: the goal of Hindu spiritual life. Achieved through moksha — the recognition of Atman\'s identity with Brahman (Advaita), devotion to God (bhakti), or right action (karma yoga). Once liberated, the soul does not reincarnate.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Buddhism — Punarbhava (Pali: Punabbhava — "renewed existence")</h3>';
echo '<p>Buddhist teaching on rebirth is unique and philosophically distinctive: Buddhism teaches rebirth without a permanent soul. This is the famous doctrine of <em>anatta</em> (no-self). If there is no permanent self, what reincarnates? The Buddhist answer: not a soul but a stream of consciousness — a causal continuity of mental and physical processes. What carries over from life to life is not an identical entity but a causal stream, like a flame passed from candle to candle: the second flame is causally related to the first but not identical with it.</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Cross-species transmigration</strong>: fully accepted. The six realms of rebirth (Samsara) include: the Hell realms (Naraka), the Hungry Ghost realm (Preta loka), the Animal realm, the Human realm, the Asura (demi-god) realm, and the Deva (god) realm. Beings cycle through all six realms according to karma. Human birth is considered the most fortunate because it is the platform from which liberation is most accessible.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Gender in reincarnation</strong>: Buddhist texts generally teach that gender changes across lives. A being may be reborn as male or female. In Theravada texts, the Bodhisatta (future Buddha) is described as having been reborn in female forms. However, certain early texts suggest that women cannot become fully enlightened Buddhas (only male Buddhas) — a position rejected by Mahayana Buddhism, which affirms that gender is ultimately irrelevant to Buddha-nature. Tantric Buddhism (Vajrayana) holds that female birth can be more spiritually potent than male birth in certain practices.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Karma</strong>: Buddhism\'s karma doctrine focuses on intention (cetana): "It is intention that I call karma." The moral quality of an action is determined by the mental state that generates it. A good action done from greed is not truly meritorious; a neutral action done from compassion generates merit. Karma operates across lives but is not fatalistic: the present moment always offers the possibility of changing one\'s karmic trajectory through mindfulness and right action.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Liberation from samsara</strong>: Nirvana — the extinguishing of craving, aversion, and delusion. The liberated being (Arahant in Theravada; Buddha in all traditions) does not reincarnate after death.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Jainism — Samsara and the Jiva</h3>';
echo '<p>Jainism has the most rigorous and comprehensive doctrine of metempsychosis in any tradition. Every living being — including plants, microorganisms, and elements — has a soul (jiva). The jiva is bound to samsara by karma — but in Jainism, karma is understood as a subtle physical substance that adheres to the soul through passionate actions. The jiva has infinite potential knowledge and bliss, but is obscured by karma-matter accumulated over innumerable lives.</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Cross-species transmigration</strong>: taken to its logical extreme. Jain cosmology classifies souls by the number of senses they possess: one-sensed beings (plants, earth-bodies, water-bodies, fire-bodies, air-bodies), two-sensed (worms, leeches), three-sensed (ants, lice), four-sensed (flies, mosquitoes), five-sensed without mind (fish, most animals), five-sensed with mind (humans, gods, hell-beings). The soul cycles through all these forms according to karma.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ahimsa (non-violence)</strong>: the supreme Jain ethical principle, rooted directly in the doctrine of metempsychosis. Since every living being has a soul, harming any being is harming a soul that might be a former relative or friend. The strictest Jain monks wear masks to avoid inhaling insects and sweep the path before them to avoid stepping on creatures.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Gender</strong>: Jain texts debate whether liberation (moksha) is possible from a female body. The Digambara sect holds that women must be reborn as men before they can achieve liberation. The Shvetambara sect (pointing to the liberated Tirthankara Malli, described as female) holds that women can achieve liberation directly.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Liberation</strong>: achieved by exhausting all existing karma and preventing new karma through non-violence, truthfulness, non-stealing, celibacy, and non-attachment. The liberated jiva (Siddha) rises to the top of the universe and remains there in perfect, infinite knowledge and bliss — never reincarnating.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Sikhism</h3>';
echo '<p>Sikhism accepts reincarnation (aavagavan — "coming and going") as the framework from which its path offers liberation. The soul (jiv atma) cycles through 8.4 million species before achieving human birth. Human birth is the rare opportunity to break the cycle through Naam Japna (meditation on God\'s name) and the Guru\'s grace (nadar). The cycle is driven by haumai (ego/self-centeredness) and its resulting karma. <strong>Gender</strong>: Sikhism explicitly affirms gender equality — the soul has no gender, and women and men have equal spiritual capacity. Liberation is available to all regardless of birth circumstances. <strong>Liberation</strong>: mukti — merger of the individual soul with God (Waheguru).</p>';

echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#553c9a;">⊕ Reincarnation in African Traditions</h2>';

echo '<h3>Ọdinala (Igbo) — Ilo Uwa</h3>';
echo '<p><em>Ilo uwa</em> — "returning to the world" — is the Igbo doctrine of reincarnation. It is one of the most distinctively <strong>lineage-specific</strong> and <strong>gender-consistent</strong> reincarnation doctrines in the world, setting it apart clearly from Hindu, Buddhist, and Greek versions.</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Gender consistency</strong>: in Igbo ilo uwa, a man returns as a man and a woman returns as a woman. There is no cross-gender reincarnation in traditional Igbo belief. The soul retains its gender identity across incarnations. This reflects the deep importance of gender roles and lineage in Igbo social structure — the patrilineage (umunna) and the matrilineal connection are fundamental to Igbo identity, and the soul\'s return within these categories maintains social and spiritual continuity.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Lineage-specific</strong>: the returning soul typically reincarnates within its own family lineage. A grandfather returns as a grandson; a grandmother as a granddaughter. This is why the names Nnenna ("my grandmother lives again"), Nnanna ("my grandfather lives again"), Nnaemeka ("my father does great things — in his reborn child"), and similar names are common. The reborn child may be recognized by physical resemblance, behavioral traits, or through divination.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Not cyclical burden but family continuity</strong>: unlike Hindu samsara (which is understood as suffering to be escaped), Igbo ilo uwa is understood primarily as a continuation of family bonds across time. The dead grandparent who returns as a grandchild is a blessing — a continuation of the family story. There is no strong drive to escape reincarnation in Igbo thought as there is in Hindu/Buddhist soteriology.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ọgbanje — the pathological case</strong>: the ọgbanje is the exception to the normal pattern of ilo uwa. An ọgbanje soul has made a pact to cycle rapidly — being born, dying young, and returning — repeatedly tormenting its mother. This is understood as a spiritual disorder: the soul has not committed to the human world but maintains a pact with the spirit world (uwa mmụọ). The cure — finding and destroying the iyi-uwa (covenant stone) — breaks this compulsive cycle and enables the soul to complete a normal human life.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Karma equivalent — Ọgụ and Ọfọ</strong>: Igbo moral causation is primarily intra-life rather than inter-life. A person with ọgụ (clean hands, moral innocence) is protected by their ancestors and their chi; a person who does wrong is vulnerable to spiritual attack and ancestral displeasure. However, the returning soul\'s conditions — the family and circumstances it is born into — reflect the quality of the previous life. A person who lived well returns to a blessed family; a person who lived badly may return to difficult circumstances. This is not elaborated as a formal inter-life karma doctrine but is implied in traditional understanding.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Yoruba — Atunwa (Return to Earth)</h3>';
echo '<p>The Yoruba doctrine of <em>atunwa</em> ("to return again") shares features with Igbo ilo uwa but has its own characteristics:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Lineage-specific</strong>: like Ọdinala, Yoruba reincarnation is primarily within the family. Babatunde ("father has returned"), Yetunde ("mother has returned"), Iyabo ("mother has come back") are names directly encoding this belief.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Gender</strong>: Yoruba tradition generally maintains gender consistency in reincarnation — a man returns as a man — though this is less rigidly defined than in Igbo tradition. The Ori (personal divine head) chosen before birth determines one\'s destiny including gender.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Karma equivalent — Iwa</strong>: the quality of one\'s character (iwa) in this life directly influences the conditions of the next incarnation. "Iwa l\'ewa" — character is beauty. Good character creates good destiny; bad character creates bad destiny. This operates both within a life (through the Orishas\' favor or disfavor) and across lives (through the quality of the next incarnation\'s Ori-choice).</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Akan — Sunsum and Rebirth</h3>';
echo '<p>Akan tradition (Ashanti, Fante — Ghana) holds that the sunsum (personal spirit) can return to the family after death. The concept of <em>mogya</em> (blood, transmitted matrilineally) means that ancestral souls return through the female line. This creates a distinctively matrilineal dimension to Akan rebirth belief — souls return through their mothers\' lineages. <strong>Gender</strong>: not rigidly specified in all sources; the focus is on the lineage connection rather than gender consistency.</p>';

echo '<h3>Kongo — The Dikenga Cycle</h3>';
echo '<p>As documented in the Esoterism/African section, the Kongo cosmogram (Dikenga dia Kongo) encodes a reincarnation cycle: the soul passes through the four phases (birth, life, death, ancestral existence) and returns. Kongo reincarnation is cosmic and cyclical rather than karma-based in the Hindu sense. The returning soul brings wisdom from its ancestral existence. <strong>Gender and species</strong>: the Kongo cosmogram does not specify cross-species transmigration; the focus is on the human-to-ancestor-to-human cycle within the community.</p>';

echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#2b6cb0;">⊕ Abrahamic Positions on Metempsychosis</h2>';

echo '<h3>Judaism</h3>';
echo '<p>Mainstream Judaism does not teach reincarnation. The Torah and Talmud describe a single human life followed by resurrection of the dead at the end of days and judgment. However, <strong>Kabbalah teaches gilgul neshamot (transmigration of souls)</strong> as a central doctrine — and Kabbalah became mainstream in Jewish mysticism from the 16th century onward, so the picture is complex:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Gilgul</strong>: souls reincarnate to complete unfulfilled mitzvot (commandments), repair past wrongs (tikkun), or achieve the spiritual level not reached in previous lives. Each soul has a specific root (shoresh) and specific missions across its incarnations.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ibbur and Dybbuk</strong>: ibbur is the temporary attachment of a righteous soul to a living person to help them fulfill a specific mission; a dybbuk is the malevolent attachment of an unrighteous soul to a living person, requiring exorcism.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Gender</strong>: Lurianic Kabbalah explicitly allows for gender change across incarnations. A male soul may reincarnate as female if it has specific tikkunim (repairs) to perform that require female incarnation.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Cross-species</strong>: some Kabbalistic texts teach that souls can incarnate in animal, plant, or mineral form as punishment or for specific spiritual purposes (gilgul be-domem, tzomeach, chai — mineral, plant, animal gilgul).</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Christianity</h3>';
echo '<p>Mainstream Christianity firmly rejects reincarnation. The definitive statement: <strong>"It is appointed for men to die once, and after that comes judgment" (Hebrews 9:27)</strong>. The Council of Constantinople (553 CE) condemned Origen\'s teachings on the pre-existence of souls — a position associated with metempsychosis. This has been the orthodox position since. However:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Origen (185–254 CE)</strong> — the greatest early Christian theologian — taught the pre-existence of souls and a form of apokatastasis (universal restoration) that many scholars interpret as compatible with multiple lives. His work was condemned but never entirely suppressed.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Cathar Christianity (12th–13th century)</strong> — the Cathars of southern France explicitly taught reincarnation as the mechanism by which souls were purified before final spiritual liberation. They were exterminated in the Albigensian Crusade (1209–1229).</li>';
echo '<li><strong>New Age Christianity and Gnostic revivals</strong> — many modern Christians (particularly influenced by New Age thought) accept reincarnation as compatible with Christian teaching, despite official Church rejection.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<h3>Islam</h3>';
echo '<p>Mainstream Sunni and Shia Islam firmly reject reincarnation. Islamic eschatology (the doctrine of last things) is linear and non-cyclical: one life, death (barzakh — the intermediate state), resurrection (qiyama), judgment, and either paradise or hell. However:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Druze</strong> — an offshoot of Ismaili Islam, the Druze community explicitly teaches reincarnation. The soul is immediately reborn at death into a new Druze body (non-Druze cannot be reborn as Druze). Gender change across incarnations is accepted.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Certain Sufi positions</strong> — a minority of Sufi thinkers have taught something compatible with reincarnation, particularly those influenced by Neoplatonism. Ibn Arabi\'s complex cosmology of the soul\'s traverse of multiple "presences" (hadarat) has been interpreted by some as implying multiple lives.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Ismaili esoterism</strong> — certain Ismaili (Shia) interpretations teach a form of spiritual return that some scholars classify as reincarnation doctrine.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

echo '<hr style="margin:28px 0;border:none;border-top:2px solid #e5e7eb;">';
echo '<h2 style="color:#744210;">⊕ Karma — Comparative Doctrine</h2>';

