echo '<h2 style="color:#276749;">⊕ The Igbo Distinction — Why It Matters</h2>';
echo '<p>The Igbo doctrine of ilo uwa is philosophically significant precisely because of what distinguishes it from the dominant world traditions:</p>';
echo '<ul>';
echo '<li><strong>Gender-consistent reincarnation</strong> — man returns as man, woman as woman — is unusual globally. Most traditions that teach reincarnation allow cross-gender incarnation (Hinduism, Buddhism, Kabbalah, Greek philosophy). The Igbo position reflects a metaphysics of gender as essential to the soul, not merely accidental to it. Gender is not a cosmic accident or a karmic condition but part of the soul\'s identity.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>Lineage-specific reincarnation</strong> — returning within one\'s own family — makes ilo uwa a philosophy of <em>family continuity across time</em> rather than a philosophy of <em>escape from suffering</em>. The Igbo cosmos is not a prison from which souls seek liberation; it is a home to which souls return with love.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>No formal soteriology of escape</strong> — unlike Hindu moksha, Buddhist nirvana, or Kabbalistic tikkun complete, Ọdinala does not have a developed theology of final liberation from the reincarnation cycle. The cycle of family return is not primarily experienced as suffering but as continuity. This is a fundamentally different metaphysical attitude — one that values embodied communal existence rather than transcendence of it.</li>';
echo '<li><strong>The ọgbanje as pathology</strong> — by identifying premature cycling (ọgbanje) as a spiritual disorder requiring healing, Ọdinala implicitly affirms that the normal pattern of reincarnation is <em>not</em> rapid and compulsive but orderly and life-completing. The soul is supposed to live a full human life before returning. This is a normative claim about what a good reincarnation looks like.</li>';
echo '</ul>';

